{
  "title": "Stoichiometry and Balancing Equations",
  "publicationStatus": "public",
  "subtitle": "Getting the ratios right.",
  "about": [
    "In writing a chemical reaction you must satisfy these two laws of chemistry:",
    "",
    "1. **The law of conservation of mass**: The mass of the reactants must equal the mass of the",
    "products.",
    "2. **The law of definite proportions**: When making a certain chemical there is only one",
    "right ratio of reactants. When making peanut butter cookies one might use different",
    "ingredients or different amounts of the same ingredients. When making hydrogen chloride or",
    "any other chemical there is only one correct recipe or ratio of reactants.",
    "",
    "**The chemical equation should be written using the simplest ratios**: An equation gives the",
    "basic recipe. There are several ratios of hydrogen to chlorine that will satisfy the above",
    "two laws. However, they all can be simplified to the 1:1:2 ratio you see in the balanced",
    "equation:",
    "",
    "H2 + Cl2 => 2 HCl",
    "",
    "Try several different ratios to see which ones form a complete reaction with nothing left",
    "over."
  ],
